  "companies": [],
  "statement": "# Rotting Oranges\n\nEach minute, rotten oranges rot adjacent fresh oranges. Return the minutes needed to rot all fresh oranges, or `-1` if impossible.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Example 1**\n\n```text\nInput: grid = [[2,1,1],[1,1,0],[0,1,1]]\nOutput: 4\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n\n```text\nInput: grid = [[2,1,1],[0,1,1],[1,0,1]]\nOutput: -1\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n\n```text\nInput: grid = [[0,2]]\nOutput: 0\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- Inputs are sized for local offline execution.\n- Return values follow the method description.",
  "editorial": "Use the graph structure directly: traverse reachable states, maintain visited or distance state, and update the answer when each node or cell is settled.",
  "solution_notes": "```python\nfrom collections import deque\n\nclass Solution:\n    def orangesRotting(self, grid):\n        rows, cols = len(grid), len(grid[0])\n        queue = deque()\n        fresh = 0\n        for r in range(rows):\n            for c in range(cols):\n                if grid[r][c] == 2:\n                    queue.append((r, c, 0))\n                elif grid[r][c] == 1:\n                    fresh += 1\n        minutes = 0\n        while queue:\n            r, c, minutes = queue.popleft()\n            for dr, dc in ((1,0),(-1,0),(0,1),(0,-1)):\n                nr, nc = r + dr, c + dc\n                if 0 <= nr < rows and 0 <= nc < cols and grid[nr][nc] == 1:\n                    grid[nr][nc] = 2\n                    fresh -= 1\n                    queue.append((nr, nc, minutes + 1))\n        return minutes if fresh == 0 else -1\n```",
  "hints": [
    "Model the state explicitly.",
    "Prefer linear or near-linear graph traversal when possible."
  ],
